00:00:03.420 --> 00:00:06.369
Prof: We're now at the
stage where we're considering

00:00:06.369 --> 00:00:10.442
the implications of uncertainty,
so I hope that the subtlety,

00:00:10.442 --> 00:00:13.390
and surprise element of the
class,

00:00:13.390 --> 00:00:18.090
will gradually pick up without
increasing the difficulty.

00:00:18.090 --> 00:00:20.466
The complexity will pick up a
little bit, but not the

00:00:20.466 --> 00:00:21.060
difficulty.
 

00:00:21.060 --> 00:00:23.599
It's just you'll have to keep a
few more things in your head,

00:00:23.599 --> 00:00:25.250
but the mathematics isn't any
harder.

00:00:25.250 --> 00:00:30.996
So we ended last time talking
about default and inferring

00:00:30.996 --> 00:00:36.127
default probabilities,
and so I just want to finish

00:00:36.127 --> 00:00:38.590
off that discussion.
 

00:00:38.590 --> 00:00:42.051
So suppose that at any stage of
the tree, you know,

00:00:42.051 --> 00:00:44.890
lots of things can happen in
the world.

00:00:44.890 --> 00:00:48.127
We're always going to model the
uncertainty in the future by a

00:00:48.127 --> 00:00:50.250
tree with different things
happening,

00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:55.327
and at each of these nodes
people are going to have a

00:00:55.327 --> 00:00:56.890
discount rate.
 

00:00:56.890 --> 00:01:02.640
So maybe it'll be r equals 20
percent,

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:08.438
and here r could equal 15
percent, something like that,

00:01:08.438 --> 00:01:12.658
and we want to add to this the
possibility that there's

00:01:12.658 --> 00:01:13.438
default.
 

00:01:13.438 --> 00:01:18.397
So if we add the possibility of
default, and these things keep

00:01:18.397 --> 00:01:22.786
going and maybe there are
payoffs at the end or payoffs

00:01:22.786 --> 00:01:24.250
along the way.
 

00:01:24.250 --> 00:01:27.430
If at any point in the tree
like this one we add a new

00:01:27.430 --> 00:01:31.522
possibility,
which is the default

00:01:31.522 --> 00:01:37.584
possibility, so this happens--
by the way, when do people

00:01:37.584 --> 00:01:37.970
default?
 

00:01:37.970 --> 00:01:40.300
They never default before they
have to make a payment.

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:42.833
So when do they default,
exactly when they're supposed

00:01:42.833 --> 00:01:43.790
to make a payment.
 

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:48.575
So suppose that this guy is
going to default here when he's

00:01:48.575 --> 00:01:50.720
going to make a payment.
 

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:53.530
At every possible scenario he
would default there.

00:01:53.530 --> 00:01:56.976
So we've got a very simple
model of default,

00:01:56.976 --> 00:02:01.704
so not a very realistic one
where the guy defaults in all of

00:02:01.704 --> 00:02:04.109
these following scenarios.
 

00:02:04.109 --> 00:02:06.099
So something's just bad.
 

00:02:06.099 --> 00:02:08.896
Once he's gotten here you know
that he's not going to make the

00:02:08.896 --> 00:02:10.090
payment the next period.
 

00:02:10.090 --> 00:02:13.413
We further assume that not only
does he default there,

00:02:13.413 --> 00:02:16.110
but he defaults on everything
thereafter.

00:02:16.110 --> 00:02:19.008
So the payoff is just going to
be 0 here.

00:02:19.008 --> 00:02:20.852
So this is going to
be--originally we had

00:02:20.852 --> 00:02:23.055
probabilities p_1,
p_2,

00:02:23.055 --> 00:02:24.771
p_3,
let's say for the

00:02:24.771 --> 00:02:28.938
probabilities,
now we're going to have

00:02:28.938 --> 00:02:37.759
probabilities d for default and
then 1 - d times all of these,

00:02:37.759 --> 00:02:38.680
right?
 

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:40.800
So essentially what have we
done?

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:44.745
We've simply replaced in our
calculation of payoffs and

00:02:44.745 --> 00:02:47.478
present values,
we've simply replaced these

00:02:47.478 --> 00:02:49.788
possibilities with probability
p_1,

00:02:49.788 --> 00:02:51.470
p_2,
p_3.

00:02:51.470 --> 00:02:54.758
We added another possibility,
but the payoffs are 0 here.

00:02:54.758 --> 00:02:57.378
Nothing's going to happen from
then on except 0,

00:02:57.378 --> 00:02:59.740
and we said that happened with
probability d,

00:02:59.740 --> 00:03:02.299
which means presumably,
all of these have to be scaled

00:03:02.299 --> 00:03:04.280
down by that so they still add
up to 1.

00:03:04.280 --> 00:03:18.110
So essentially the point I'm
trying to make is that default

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:29.080
that leads to 0 payoffs
thereafter is just like

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:34.090
discounting more.
 

00:03:34.090 --> 00:03:34.960
Why is that?
 

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:38.662
Because whatever calculation
you did for the value here of

00:03:38.662 --> 00:03:41.910
what the bond could possibly be
worth there is--

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:45.147
it's all the same numbers as
there were before except we've

00:03:45.147 --> 00:03:48.910
multiplied it by 1 - d,
so it's the same thing.

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:57.622
So instead of going 1 over 1 r
times future payoffs,

00:03:57.622 --> 00:04:07.188
that's no default value,
so that times future payoffs.

00:04:07.188 --> 00:04:13.679
Now we've got default value
under this special kind of

00:04:13.679 --> 00:04:20.903
default is going to be 1 - d
times 1 over 1 r times the same

00:04:20.903 --> 00:04:23.230
future payoffs.
 

00:04:23.230 --> 00:04:29.139
I could rewrite 1 - d as 1 over
1 s or something,

00:04:29.139 --> 00:04:36.649
and so then I really have just
1 over 1 r times 1 over 1 s.

00:04:36.649 --> 00:04:41.800
So that's just 1 over (1 r s r
s).

00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:55.379
So that's going to equal 1 over
(1 r s r s) times future values.

00:04:55.379 --> 00:04:59.600
So the effect of this special
kind of default--we just get 0

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:00.528
thereafter.
 

00:05:00.528 --> 00:05:02.913
The guy decides after this
payment, "I'm not going to

00:05:02.913 --> 00:05:03.959
make any more payments.
 

00:05:03.959 --> 00:05:05.439
I'm defaulting from then
on."

00:05:05.439 --> 00:05:10.079
That's the same thing when
valuing the future payoffs,

00:05:10.079 --> 00:05:13.528
it's the same thing as instead
of discounting by r,

00:05:13.528 --> 00:05:18.899
discounting by r s with a
little bit r times s.

00:05:18.899 --> 00:05:20.899
If r and s are small numbers
this [r times s]

00:05:20.899 --> 00:05:22.490
is probably quite a small
number.

00:05:22.490 --> 00:05:30.300
So default probabilities get
mapped into spreads they're

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:31.579
called.
 

00:05:31.579 --> 00:05:36.430
They way to evaluate it is just
you just multiply it by 1 - d,

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:39.730
which is the same thing as
discounting by a higher number,

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:42.600
and that higher number is
almost the same.

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:46.103
It's very close to r d,
as a matter of fact,

00:05:46.103 --> 00:05:48.550
because 1 - d is 1 over 1 s.
 

00:05:48.550 --> 00:06:01.680
If d is very small s is going
to be very close to d as well.

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:03.360
So what's the implication of
this?

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:10.752
The implication of this in a
special case again where we just

00:06:10.752 --> 00:06:16.420
have no uncertainty,
except we have default.

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:19.278
So here there could be
d_1,

00:06:19.278 --> 00:06:22.420
1 - d_1 and here
there could be probability of

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:27.232
default 2 and 1 - d_2,
probability of default 3,1 -

00:06:27.232 --> 00:06:30.870
d_3,
and we've got interest rates

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:35.959
r_0--
so this will be i_0,

00:06:35.959 --> 00:06:40.940
i^(F)_1,
i^(F)_2.

00:06:40.940 --> 00:06:44.067
So if you knew what the
interest rate was going to be

00:06:44.067 --> 00:06:45.668
today,
you knew what the interest rate

00:06:45.668 --> 00:06:47.735
was going to be tomorrow,
you knew what the interest rate

00:06:47.735 --> 00:06:49.250
was going to be the day after
tomorrow,

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:51.120
there's no uncertainty about
interest rates,

00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:52.894
they're perfectly
anticipatable,

00:06:52.894 --> 00:06:55.983
but you know that there's a
probability of default each

00:06:55.983 --> 00:06:56.500
time.
 

00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:59.956
So in stage 1 this guy might
default before making his

00:06:59.956 --> 00:07:02.826
payment here,
which case you're just going to

00:07:02.826 --> 00:07:03.480
get 0.
 

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:07.033
In stage 2 he might default
instead of making his payment,

00:07:07.033 --> 00:07:09.528
won't pay the coupon,
he'll just default,

00:07:09.528 --> 00:07:11.649
or in year 3 he might default.
 

00:07:11.649 --> 00:07:17.350
So what's the implication of
what we just said?

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:23.088
You can evaluate this bond,
the payoffs of the bond,

00:07:23.088 --> 00:07:28.040
so let's say it pays a coupon,
C, C 100 C.

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:31.728
All right, the way you would
evaluate that without default is

00:07:31.728 --> 00:07:34.620
you would just take the value of
the coupon,

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:41.124
the present value would have
been--you would have done it

00:07:41.124 --> 00:07:42.750
recursively.
 

00:07:42.750 --> 00:07:48.649
You would have gotten
P_3 = 100 C.

00:07:48.649 --> 00:07:51.230
Then you would have said
P_2,

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.040
you would have gone in your
computer--

00:07:53.040 --> 00:08:00.475
you would have said
P_2 is 1 over (1

00:08:00.475 --> 00:08:05.930
i^(F)_2) times 100 C.
 

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:09.829
So the value here is the 100 C
discounted by that forward rate,

00:08:09.829 --> 00:08:15.132
then P_1 would have
been (C P_2) divided

00:08:15.132 --> 00:08:17.560
by (1 i^(F)_1).
 

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:19.420
So you take the value here
times that,

00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:21.060
so this is case there's no
default,

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:27.975
and P_0 would have
been (C P_1) over (1

00:08:27.975 --> 00:08:30.480
i^(F)_0).
 

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:33.139
So that's how you would have
done it by backward induction.

00:08:33.139 --> 00:08:37.461
But now that you know there's a
chance that there's default you

00:08:37.461 --> 00:08:40.668
have to not multiply by 1
i^(F)_2.

00:08:40.668 --> 00:08:44.764
You have to multiply all these
things by the probability of

00:08:44.764 --> 00:08:45.470
default.
 

00:08:45.470 --> 00:08:51.616
So you'd have to multiply this
by, if we change colors,

00:08:51.616 --> 00:08:52.870
by 1 - d.
 

00:08:52.870 --> 00:08:58.730
You have to multiply this by 1
- d_2,

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:03.750
and you'd have to multiply this
by (1 - d_1) times (1

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:07.597
- d_2),
and this by 1 -,

00:09:07.597 --> 00:09:13.028
sorry this would be 1 -
d_3.

00:09:13.028 --> 00:09:17.072
This is (1 - d_3)
times d_2,

00:09:17.072 --> 00:09:22.404
and this is (1 - d_1)
times (1 - d_2) times

00:09:22.404 --> 00:09:24.470
(1 - d_3).
 

00:09:24.470 --> 00:09:27.993
So this value would be the old
value you got here multiplied by

00:09:27.993 --> 00:09:30.606
1 - d_3,
multiplied by this one minus

00:09:30.606 --> 00:09:31.629
d_3.
 

00:09:31.629 --> 00:09:34.240
This value is what you would
have gotten here,

00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:37.374
but you've already scaled it
down, so multiplied by 1 -

00:09:37.374 --> 00:09:40.159
d_2 and this is 1 -
d_1.

00:09:40.159 --> 00:09:45.950
So what's the upshot?
 

00:09:45.950 --> 00:09:53.090
So that gives you the price
with default.

00:09:53.090 --> 00:09:53.720
Student: Professor?
 

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:54.480
