00:14:58.240 --> 00:15:03.929
So that was supposed to be
obvious even though I made it

00:15:03.929 --> 00:15:06.000
sound complicated.
 

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:23.957
What's slightly subtler is just
saying the same thing backwards

00:15:23.957 --> 00:15:38.730
which is, suppose I knew all
these forward rates.

00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:51.154
Suppose I had a bunch of bonds,
suppose I had American bonds,

00:15:51.154 --> 00:15:54.259
coupon bonds.
 

00:15:54.259 --> 00:15:57.690
So the American coupon bonds
are going to pay,

00:15:57.690 --> 00:16:02.035
you know, the 1-year pays a
coupon C_1 and has a

00:16:02.035 --> 00:16:05.620
face of 100 and has a price
Pi_1.

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:08.616
The 2-year American bond has a
coupon C_2,

00:16:08.616 --> 00:16:11.379
a face of 100,
and a price of Pi_2.

00:16:11.379 --> 00:16:14.846
And let's say the 5-year has
something, C_5,

00:16:14.846 --> 00:16:17.658
a face of 100 and a price
Pi_5.

00:16:17.658 --> 00:16:23.121
Now from that we know that we
can deduce what all the forwards

00:16:23.121 --> 00:16:23.659
are.
 

00:16:23.659 --> 00:16:30.460
We did that in the first class.
 

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:37.288
So now suppose at the same time
we have Argentina.

00:16:37.288 --> 00:16:41.230
Many Argentine sovereign bonds
promise payments in dollars,

00:16:41.230 --> 00:16:45.240
by the way, they're trying to
trade them internationally.

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:49.552
So let's say we also have the
Argentina bonds

00:16:49.552 --> 00:16:54.359
C-hat_1,
100, Pi-hat_1,

00:16:54.359 --> 00:16:58.398
that's the 1-year,
down to the 5-year which is the

00:16:58.398 --> 00:17:03.471
Argentina C-hat_5,
100 and Pi-hat_5,

00:17:03.471 --> 00:17:04.848
its price.
 

00:17:04.848 --> 00:17:10.279
Now, let's suppose that
Argentina could default whereas

00:17:10.279 --> 00:17:11.890
America can't.
 

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:14.596
So it's quite likely that
Pi-hat_1 will be less

00:17:14.596 --> 00:17:17.641
than the American Pi_1
and Pi-hat_5 is going

00:17:17.641 --> 00:17:20.009
to be less than the American
Pi_5,

00:17:20.009 --> 00:17:22.019
because all these bonds might
default.

00:17:22.019 --> 00:17:24.544
So if the coupons were the
same, if C-hat_1 was

00:17:24.544 --> 00:17:27.203
the same as C_1 and
C-hat_5 was the same

00:17:27.203 --> 00:17:29.593
as C_5 the fact that
Argentina could default

00:17:29.593 --> 00:17:32.028
obviously would mean its bonds
would trade less for the

00:17:32.028 --> 00:17:33.019
American ones.
 

00:17:33.019 --> 00:17:37.169
So the question is can you
figure out the default

00:17:37.169 --> 00:17:42.441
probabilities very quickly in
Argentina without having to do a

00:17:42.441 --> 00:17:47.240
lot of complicated calculations,
and the answer is yes.

00:17:47.240 --> 00:17:48.058
And why is that?
 

00:17:48.058 --> 00:17:51.729
Because you could take this
data and you could say--so we

00:17:51.729 --> 00:17:53.630
could just erase this here.
 

00:17:53.630 --> 00:18:00.997
We could say,
assuming no default,

00:18:00.997 --> 00:18:10.818
we could explain these prices
by finding,

00:18:10.818 --> 00:18:18.700
just like we did the America,
the Argentine forwards,

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:27.807
1 i-hat_0,
1 i-hat^(F)_1 and 1

00:18:27.807 --> 00:18:32.269
i-hat^(F)_4.
 

00:18:32.269 --> 00:18:34.029
So these are the Argentine
forwards.

00:18:34.029 --> 00:18:37.214
Now, these forwards would be
much bigger than the American

00:18:37.214 --> 00:18:37.829
forwards.
 

00:18:37.829 --> 00:18:38.828
Why is that?
 

00:18:38.828 --> 00:18:42.720
Because the prices in Argentina
are so much lower.

00:18:42.720 --> 00:18:46.325
If you're assuming there is no
default, assuming no default,

00:18:46.325 --> 00:18:49.257
contrary to fact,
how could you explain all these

00:18:49.257 --> 00:18:50.480
very low prices?
 

00:18:50.480 --> 00:18:53.707
Well, you must think that in
Argentina they've got very high

00:18:53.707 --> 00:18:55.950
interest rates and very high
forwards,

00:18:55.950 --> 00:18:59.298
so they're discounting more and
that's why they've got lower

00:18:59.298 --> 00:18:59.808
prices.
 

00:18:59.808 --> 00:19:02.479
And we know how to get those
forwards assuming there was no

00:19:02.479 --> 00:19:02.940
default.
 

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:05.660
So the trick,
I'm merely pointing out now,

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:10.170
is that if we now go back and
say, ah ha,

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:13.163
Argentina doesn't have
different forwards because

00:19:13.163 --> 00:19:16.217
anyone in Argentina--
the bonds are denominated in

00:19:16.217 --> 00:19:19.740
dollars precisely so that people
can be crossover investors.

00:19:19.740 --> 00:19:22.048
An American can put his money
in Argentina.

00:19:22.048 --> 00:19:25.567
An Argentine can put his money
in America, so you can move your

00:19:25.567 --> 00:19:26.930
money to either place.
 

00:19:26.930 --> 00:19:30.598
So it must be that the forward
rates can't be different.

00:19:30.598 --> 00:19:33.374
If you knew for sure you were
going to get paid in Argentina

00:19:33.374 --> 00:19:35.960
you'd have to have the same
forward rates in America.

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:39.200
So the reason these forward
rates are higher is because

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:41.000
there's a chance of default.
 

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:44.548
So what is the chance of
default?

00:19:44.548 --> 00:19:47.008
So I claim the chance of
default is, and I was

00:19:47.008 --> 00:19:49.740
supposedly--you're supposed to
realize this now.

00:19:49.740 --> 00:19:54.970
If I'd been clearer before you
would see where I'm going.

00:19:54.970 --> 00:19:57.650
The chance of default is
incredibly simple to find out.

00:19:57.650 --> 00:20:06.450
So it's 1 - d_t =
what?

00:20:06.450 --> 00:20:08.328
Student:
&gt;

00:20:08.328 --> 00:20:12.000
Prof: But in terms of
forwards is what?

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.548
It's not Pi--this Pi,
this isn't the 0 price.

00:20:14.548 --> 00:20:17.680
This is the big price of the
bonds.

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:22.650
So it's not Pi-hat_t
over Pi_t.

00:20:22.650 --> 00:20:27.038
What is it though?
 

00:20:27.038 --> 00:20:29.230
Student: The ratio of
forwards?

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:38.828
Student: Pi_t
- &gt;

00:20:38.828 --> 00:20:45.631
Prof: This is going to
be a bigger number than that,

00:20:45.631 --> 00:20:51.730
and in fact that ratio is the
default probability.

00:20:51.730 --> 00:20:55.249
So this is assuming,
remember, that if the Argentine

00:20:55.249 --> 00:20:59.182
bond defaults at this period,
say, it's never going to pay

00:20:59.182 --> 00:21:00.838
anything after that.
 

00:21:00.838 --> 00:21:04.179
You're going to get 0 pay off
and all the other Argentine

00:21:04.179 --> 00:21:05.730
bonds will also default.
 

00:21:05.730 --> 00:21:07.703
I claim that this [note:
meaning, (1 - d_t =

00:21:07.703 --> 00:21:09.864
(1 i^(F)_t-1) over (1
i-hat^(F)_t-1)) ]

00:21:09.864 --> 00:21:12.358
is going to be the easy way of
getting the default probability.

00:21:12.358 --> 00:21:15.929
And so the differences in the
forwards is just explained by

00:21:15.929 --> 00:21:19.930
the default probabilities and so
the extra Argentine interest,

00:21:19.930 --> 00:21:22.624
if this [the denominator]
is a higher number than that

00:21:22.624 --> 00:21:26.670
[the numerator],
1 - d is approximately 1 over

00:21:26.670 --> 00:21:30.576
(1 d),
and so it's basically if all

00:21:30.576 --> 00:21:37.016
the numbers i and d are small
then i-hat^(F)_t - 1

00:21:37.016 --> 00:21:41.710
is approximately i^(F)_t -
1,

00:21:41.710 --> 00:21:45.263
the American one,
plus this default rate in

00:21:45.263 --> 00:21:46.279
Argentina.
 

00:21:46.279 --> 00:21:50.680
So I should probably have a hat
because I'm referring to

00:21:50.680 --> 00:21:52.680
Argentina with the hat.
 

00:21:52.680 --> 00:21:53.680
So why is that true.
 

00:21:53.680 --> 00:21:54.599
I just argued it.
 

00:21:54.599 --> 00:22:01.808
How could that possibly be true?
 

00:22:01.808 --> 00:22:06.111
So you see what I'm claiming
that you have now a very simple

00:22:06.111 --> 00:22:09.756
algorithm for finding out,
inferring what Argentina

00:22:09.756 --> 00:22:11.358
default rates are.
 

00:22:11.358 --> 00:22:14.345
Again, I'm making a special
assumption that when Argentina

00:22:14.345 --> 00:22:15.759
defaults you get nothing.
 

00:22:15.759 --> 00:22:17.068
That really isn't the case.
 

00:22:17.068 --> 00:22:19.505
There's some huge convention
that happens and all the

00:22:19.505 --> 00:22:21.519
countries get together they
defaulted on.

00:22:21.519 --> 00:22:24.443
They've got some big meeting,
and someone like Brady invents

00:22:24.443 --> 00:22:27.567
some idea where they'll owe less
and they will be a writing down

00:22:27.567 --> 00:22:29.400
of principal,
by the way.

00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:39.086
So whenever this happens there
is recovery after a writing down

00:22:39.086 --> 00:22:41.430
of principal.
 

00:22:41.430 --> 00:22:43.483
So what all the countries do is
they say, "Okay,

00:22:43.483 --> 00:22:45.420
we know that you can't pay all
that you owe us.

00:22:45.420 --> 00:22:47.380
We'll settle for half of it.
 

00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:50.679
We'll write down the principal
and we'll hold you to that half,

00:22:50.679 --> 00:22:51.848
or to a third of it.
 

00:22:51.848 --> 00:22:54.497
So this is one of the things we
curiously haven't done in

00:22:54.497 --> 00:22:56.859
America where all these
homeowners can't pay and we

00:22:56.859 --> 00:22:58.608
don't write down their
principal.

00:22:58.608 --> 00:23:00.078
We just throw them out of their
houses.

00:23:00.078 --> 00:23:04.250
But anyway, let's say you wrote
the principal down to 0 in that

00:23:04.250 --> 00:23:05.259
special case.
 

00:23:05.259 --> 00:23:08.818
You could easily infer from the
price of the Argentine bonds

00:23:08.818 --> 00:23:12.380
what the default probabilities
were, and by this formula.

00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:17.670
And so the question is,
why is that true?

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:21.144
We know how to calculate the
forwards in America given the

00:23:21.144 --> 00:23:22.118
American data.
 

00:23:22.118 --> 00:23:23.920
That's was one of the first
things we did in class.

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:27.181
We said that every American
company in the whole country,

00:23:27.181 --> 00:23:29.220
financial company,
is doing that.

00:23:29.220 --> 00:23:32.048
Everybody has those forwards
calculated.

00:23:32.048 --> 00:23:34.318
Now, if you're given the
Argentine data,

00:23:34.318 --> 00:23:36.906
which is, after all,
just coupons and the prices of

00:23:36.906 --> 00:23:38.911
the bonds,
you could find Argentine

00:23:38.911 --> 00:23:41.019
forwards assuming there's no
default.

00:23:41.019 --> 00:23:44.534
But there is default,
so it must be that they have

00:23:44.534 --> 00:23:48.048
access to the American interest
rates in forwards,

00:23:48.048 --> 00:23:50.990
but the Argentine bond might
default.

00:23:50.990 --> 00:23:53.519
Do you see what we did when we
did this calculation?

00:23:53.519 --> 00:23:57.596
The difference between the
backward induction in America

00:23:57.596 --> 00:24:01.526
from here to here was just
discounting by the American

00:24:01.526 --> 00:24:04.364
forward--
to go to Argentina we had to

00:24:04.364 --> 00:24:08.180
discount by the American forward
and multiply by 1 - d,

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:09.769
so discounting it again.
 

00:24:09.769 --> 00:24:11.450
So all I'm saying is that in
the U.S.

00:24:11.450 --> 00:24:16.288
when we went backwards we just
discounted by this thing.

00:24:16.288 --> 00:24:27.342
In Argentina when you go
backwards you have to discount

00:24:27.342 --> 00:24:36.346
by this thing,
so those things have to be the

00:24:36.346 --> 00:24:38.190
same.
 

00:24:38.190 --> 00:24:43.328
So the Argentinian discount is
like taking the--

00:24:43.328 --> 00:24:45.290
I hope I haven't got the
thing--so the American forwards

00:24:45.290 --> 00:24:47.109
are going to be less than the
Argentine forwards.

00:24:47.109 --> 00:24:51.829
It's going to be like that.
 

00:24:51.829 --> 00:24:52.480
So that's it.
 

00:24:52.480 --> 00:24:55.852
There's nothing else to show
except that whenever you're

00:24:55.852 --> 00:24:58.490
going backwards here you're
discounting--

00:24:58.490 --> 00:25:02.491
remember, you're discounting by
the interest rate times the

00:25:02.491 --> 00:25:06.150
probability that you're actually
going to pay off,

00:25:06.150 --> 00:25:13.829
so that's what it is in
Argentina.

00:25:13.829 --> 00:25:16.660
Hang on.
 

00:25:16.660 --> 00:25:23.471
I hope I haven't inverted one
of these, yeah,

00:25:23.471 --> 00:25:25.019
exactly.
 

00:25:25.019 --> 00:25:28.069
So if you write 1 - d times the
American thing in the

00:25:28.069 --> 00:25:29.621
denominator,
so as I said,

00:25:29.621 --> 00:25:32.308
to do the discounting in
Argentina at every step from

00:25:32.308 --> 00:25:35.410
going back from here to here
what did we do in Argentina?

00:25:35.410 --> 00:25:39.692
We simply took 1 - d-hat,
that was the default

00:25:39.692 --> 00:25:44.260
rate--hat--in Argentina,
and discounted it at the

00:25:44.260 --> 00:25:46.259
American forward.
 

00:25:46.259 --> 00:25:48.130
So that's what I did here.
 

00:25:48.130 --> 00:25:52.387
So if I take 1 - d-hat,
this is multiplied by 1,

00:25:52.387 --> 00:25:57.009
so I take 1 - d-hat^(
)multiplied by 1 over this.

00:25:57.009 --> 00:26:00.180
I just get one over the
Argentine discount,

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:02.969
and that's how we
calculated--that's how we went

00:26:02.969 --> 00:26:06.650
backwards with our recursion
just taking the interest rate,

00:26:06.650 --> 00:26:11.064
the discount 1 over (1 i) times
(1 - d) and that's how we

00:26:11.064 --> 00:26:13.348
discounted going backwards.
 

00:26:13.348 --> 00:26:15.690
And so therefore in Argentina
if you're forgetting that

00:26:15.690 --> 00:26:18.421
there's default and you're just
thinking you have to discount at

00:26:18.421 --> 00:26:20.719
the right rate and you're
getting this discount you're

00:26:20.719 --> 00:26:23.371
getting this number,
but in reality you should have

00:26:23.371 --> 00:26:25.048
been taking this divided by
that.

00:26:25.048 --> 00:26:28.888
So therefore figuring out this
and knowing that tells you what

00:26:28.888 --> 00:26:29.960
this has to be.
 

00:26:29.960 --> 00:26:33.497
So it's extremely simple to
deduce what the market thinks

00:26:33.497 --> 00:26:36.593
Argentinian default
probabilities are year by year

00:26:36.593 --> 00:26:40.319
if you make the added assumption
that once they default they

00:26:40.319 --> 00:26:41.900
default completely.
 

00:26:41.900 --> 00:26:44.592
And if you think you're only
going to get a little bit back,

00:26:44.592 --> 00:26:46.920
well then the calculation won't
change that much.

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:48.180
Yeah?
 

00:26:48.180 --> 00:26:51.750
Student: Can we also do
it by using the price of 0s?

00:26:51.750 --> 00:26:53.426
Prof: Yeah,
so you could also do it by

00:26:53.426 --> 00:26:56.316
using the price of 0s,
but to me the best thing is,

00:26:56.316 --> 00:26:59.220
the easiest thing is using the
forwards,

00:26:59.220 --> 00:27:01.279
but you can also do it by 0s.
 

00:27:01.279 --> 00:27:05.019
So that's all I wanted to say.
 

00:27:05.019 --> 00:27:11.132
As I said, the one last thing
to say is that if these numbers

00:27:11.132 --> 00:27:17.040
are all small then 1 over 1 -
d--or, 1 - d is approximately

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:19.690
equal to 1 over (1 d).
 

00:27:19.690 --> 00:27:23.808
If d is very small those are
practically the same things.

00:27:23.808 --> 00:27:29.520
Then if you multiply 1 over (1
d) by 1 over (1 i) it's almost 1

00:27:29.520 --> 00:27:33.390
over (1 d i),
so it's almost this thing.

00:27:33.390 --> 00:27:34.890
It's not quite true,
literally true,

00:27:34.890 --> 00:27:38.327
but it's very close to say that
the gap between Argentinian

00:27:38.327 --> 00:27:41.942
forwards and American forwards
is just the default probability

00:27:41.942 --> 00:27:45.855
in Argentina,
and that reason is why it's

00:27:45.855 --> 00:27:48.490
called a default spread.
 

00:27:48.490 --> 00:27:50.900
You just add some spread to the
interest rate.

00:27:50.900 --> 00:27:54.729
You can guess by the spread
what the probability of default

00:27:54.729 --> 00:27:55.058
is.
 

00:27:55.058 --> 00:27:59.213
If it's 8 percent interest
there and 3 percent interest

00:27:59.213 --> 00:28:03.444
here somebody must think the
probability of default is 5

00:28:03.444 --> 00:28:04.829
percent there.
 

00:28:04.829 --> 00:28:09.650
That's it.
 

00:28:09.650 --> 00:28:15.625
So let's now move to a tree
where you have to make

00:28:15.625 --> 00:28:17.088
decisions.
 

00:28:17.088 --> 00:28:21.271
So I'm going to now describe
the method of backward induction

00:28:21.271 --> 00:28:24.410
which occurs over and over and
over again,

00:28:24.410 --> 00:28:26.180
and we've used it a couple of
times,

00:28:26.180 --> 00:28:33.779
but not in its subtlest form,
so backward induction.

00:28:33.779 --> 00:28:36.950
Now, who first invested the
idea of backward induction?

00:28:36.950 --> 00:28:41.792
Well, the first person who
spelled it out formally was

00:28:41.792 --> 00:28:45.086
Zermelo in 1910,
I think, that's within a couple

00:28:45.086 --> 00:28:47.282
of years,
a famous mathematician,

00:28:47.282 --> 00:28:49.068
Fraenkel-Zermelo Axioms.
 

00:28:49.068 --> 00:29:02.596
And he proved that chess--that
there's an optimal strategy in

00:29:02.596 --> 00:29:09.358
chess by backward induction.
 

00:29:09.358 --> 00:29:12.220
So, for example,
let's take a game.

00:29:12.220 --> 00:29:15.836
We always are on a tree,
but now we're going to use a

00:29:15.836 --> 00:29:18.690
slightly extended definition of
a tree.

00:29:18.690 --> 00:29:20.368
A tree is going to look like
this.

00:29:20.368 --> 00:29:23.127
So it's a root,
a finite number of branches

00:29:23.127 --> 00:29:26.608
from every--I don't want to
formally define a tree.

00:29:26.608 --> 00:29:29.040
You know what it sort of looks
like, and there's no reason why

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:31.511
the number of branches has to be
two or even has to be the same

00:29:31.511 --> 00:29:32.348
from every point.
 

00:29:32.348 --> 00:29:35.663
But the reason we're going to
extend it is,

00:29:35.663 --> 00:29:39.529
the node is going to be
described by who moves.

00:29:39.529 --> 00:29:43.828
So let's say white is moving
here and black is moving here.

00:29:43.828 --> 00:29:50.106
Now, let's say the outcomes are
a win for white,

00:29:50.106 --> 00:29:55.048
a win for black,
a draw, or a draw.

00:29:55.048 --> 00:29:58.160
So the question is,
so it's a two-move chess game,

00:29:58.160 --> 00:30:01.480
white moves first up or down,
and then after white moves

00:30:01.480 --> 00:30:04.380
black moves up or down and then
the game ends.

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:07.634
And depending on where,
position you reach either it's

00:30:07.634 --> 00:30:09.599
a win for white,
a win for black,

00:30:09.599 --> 00:30:10.460
or a draw.
 

00:30:10.460 --> 00:30:12.420
So what should white do?
 

00:30:12.420 --> 00:30:20.519
Assuming that black is a smart
player what should she do?

00:30:20.519 --> 00:30:22.009
So what did Zermelo do?
 

00:30:22.009 --> 00:30:24.242
He said not only there is an
optimal strategy,

00:30:24.242 --> 00:30:27.420
but you know what the outcome
should be with rational players.

00:30:27.420 --> 00:30:32.285
So Zermelo said if white goes
up then black is clearly going

00:30:32.285 --> 00:30:34.759
to go down and win the game.
 

00:30:34.759 --> 00:30:37.535
So white ought to be thinking
here, if I go up,

00:30:37.535 --> 00:30:40.551
the game, although it won't end
for another period,

00:30:40.551 --> 00:30:41.880
it's already lost.
 

00:30:41.880 --> 00:30:45.098
So the value of the game is
already 0.

00:30:45.098 --> 00:30:48.588
So this method of backward
induction attaches the value.

00:30:48.588 --> 00:30:52.535
Here we have values at the end,
and so to figure out what the

00:30:52.535 --> 00:30:56.678
right thing to do is by backward
induction you can propagate the

00:30:56.678 --> 00:30:58.058
values backwards.
 

00:30:58.058 --> 00:31:02.463
If black makes the right choice
here the payoff is black gets

00:31:02.463 --> 00:31:06.328
the negative of white,
so the right choices here are

00:31:06.328 --> 00:31:09.410
black could get negative 1 or
could get 0,

00:31:09.410 --> 00:31:11.230
so black clearly wants to get 0.
 

00:31:11.230 --> 00:31:14.563
So black could win the game by
moving down, so black surely

00:31:14.563 --> 00:31:15.538
will move down.
 

00:31:15.538 --> 00:31:18.960
So I should think of the game
as already lost here and pretend

00:31:18.960 --> 00:31:22.324
that I had a shorter tree with
the final valuation of zero at

00:31:22.324 --> 00:31:23.108
this node.
 

00:31:23.108 --> 00:31:26.807
Similarly, if white goes down
it doesn't matter what black

00:31:26.807 --> 00:31:29.210
does the game is going to be
drawn.

00:31:29.210 --> 00:31:32.548
So white should think to
himself the game is already a

00:31:32.548 --> 00:31:33.808
draw if I go down.
 

00:31:33.808 --> 00:31:36.621
And now white has an easy
choice, do I want to move to a

00:31:36.621 --> 00:31:38.410
loss or do I want to move a
draw.

00:31:38.410 --> 00:31:42.150
So I could just pick a move for
black here.

00:31:42.150 --> 00:31:46.335
Clearly white is going to go
down and therefore with correct

00:31:46.335 --> 00:31:48.180
play the game is a draw.
 

00:31:48.180 --> 00:31:51.150
So by backward induction you
figure out the correct play.

00:31:51.150 --> 00:31:52.578
Now, why is this surprising?
 

00:31:52.578 --> 00:31:55.898
Because chess has an incredibly
big tree, not an infinite tree,

00:31:55.898 --> 00:31:58.470
there are all these rules that
keep it finite.

00:31:58.470 --> 00:32:01.657
If you reach to the same
position three times it's

00:32:01.657 --> 00:32:02.960
considered a draw.
 

00:32:02.960 --> 00:32:06.137
If you make something like 50
moves in a row without a pawn

00:32:06.137 --> 00:32:07.288
moving it's a draw.
 

00:32:07.288 --> 00:32:10.950
Whatever those rules are--I
used to play chess quite a bit.

00:32:10.950 --> 00:32:11.730
I've even forgotten.
 

00:32:11.730 --> 00:32:14.125
But whatever those rules are
they're designed to make the

00:32:14.125 --> 00:32:15.710
game finite, so the tree is
finite.

00:32:15.710 --> 00:32:18.560
And so it's impossible to see
the whole tree,

00:32:18.560 --> 00:32:22.058
and how should you know what to
do at the beginning?

00:32:22.058 --> 00:32:23.897
Well, you don't know what to do
at the beginning until you know

00:32:23.897 --> 00:32:25.470
what black's going to do
afterwards, and so what could

00:32:25.470 --> 00:32:26.328
happen later in the tree.
 

00:32:26.328 --> 00:32:29.025
But if you were fast enough to
put the whole thing on a

00:32:29.025 --> 00:32:32.068
computer you could figure out
what to do at the beginning,

00:32:32.068 --> 00:32:34.726
because your best move at the
beginning depends on what you

00:32:34.726 --> 00:32:37.509
think black is going to do next,
which depends on what he thinks

00:32:37.509 --> 00:32:40.106
you're going to do after that,
which depends on what you think

00:32:40.106 --> 00:32:41.038
he'll do after that.
 

00:32:41.038 --> 00:32:43.731
But if the tree ends you can
always go backward from the end

00:32:43.731 --> 00:32:46.151
to the beginning and figure out
what to do at the very

00:32:46.151 --> 00:32:46.788
beginning.
 

00:32:46.788 --> 00:32:49.445
So this is a familiar argument
to all of you,

00:32:49.445 --> 00:32:50.048
I think.
 

00:32:50.048 --> 00:32:55.482
It was a beautiful argument in
chess in 1910 and then it was

00:32:55.482 --> 00:32:59.720
anticipated--I mean,
in mathematics in 1910.

00:32:59.720 --> 00:33:01.720
The chess players,
of course, all knew about it,

00:33:01.720 --> 00:33:08.558
so Steinitz who was a world
champion from when to when,

00:33:08.558 --> 00:33:14.829
something like 1870 or so to,
or 1880 let's say to let's see,

00:33:14.829 --> 00:33:18.108
19,21, to 1894.
 

00:33:18.108 --> 00:33:19.599
I think he was world champion
from then to there.

00:33:19.599 --> 00:33:22.140
Lasker became the champion then.
 

00:33:22.140 --> 00:33:26.271
So he wrote a bunch of books
and stuff in which he said

00:33:26.271 --> 00:33:29.868
there's a backward induction
value to chess,

00:33:29.868 --> 00:33:33.324
but since we can't figure that
out on general principles you

00:33:33.324 --> 00:33:36.720
can tell by looking at the
configuration of pieces what the

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:44.435
right possible move is,
and so you can have positional

00:33:44.435 --> 00:33:47.440
values,
so I'll do that,

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:51.348
and then you can have the
backward induction values.

00:33:51.348 --> 00:33:56.143
So for instance a positional
value might tell you that having

00:33:56.143 --> 00:34:00.076
doubled pawns is a bad thing,
having control of the center's

00:34:00.076 --> 00:34:02.967
a good thing and you add up all
those pluses and minuses and you

00:34:02.967 --> 00:34:04.390
get these positional values.
 

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:11.039
And so he said if you've got
the right positional algorithm,

00:34:11.039 --> 00:34:14.231
right positional understanding,
your positional sense of what

00:34:14.231 --> 00:34:16.655
to do,
you only need to analyze one

00:34:16.655 --> 00:34:17.420
move deep.
 

00:34:17.420 --> 00:34:19.916
You can figure out what the
best position's going to be and

00:34:19.916 --> 00:34:21.807
move that way,
and if you really understand

00:34:21.807 --> 00:34:23.670
the game properly that
positional thinking,

00:34:23.670 --> 00:34:26.909
that strategic thinking,
so it's called strategic

00:34:26.909 --> 00:34:30.083
thinking,
is going to give you the same

00:34:30.083 --> 00:34:33.751
decision as the exhaustive
analysis of all the

00:34:33.751 --> 00:34:37.500
possibilities which was tactical
thinking,

00:34:37.500 --> 00:34:39.590
so the two should amount to the
same thing.

00:34:39.590 --> 00:34:41.251
Now, in fact,
people can't do the full

00:34:41.251 --> 00:34:43.811
tactical thing and also they
don't have the full strategic

00:34:43.811 --> 00:34:46.456
understanding either,
so they kind of mix strategy

00:34:46.456 --> 00:34:49.409
and tactics and that's what
makes the game interesting.

00:34:49.409 --> 00:34:52.344
So no one has ever written
this, but I'm sure there's an

00:34:52.344 --> 00:34:55.547
interesting study to be made
about what games are interesting

00:34:55.547 --> 00:34:58.590
and they must be the kinds of
games where there's always a

00:34:58.590 --> 00:35:00.619
mixture of strategy and tactics.
 

00:35:00.619 --> 00:35:02.925
In game theory,
as we describe it in economics,

00:35:02.925 --> 00:35:04.730
there's no such thing as
strategy.

00:35:04.730 --> 00:35:05.730
All this is out.
 

00:35:05.730 --> 00:35:08.068
It's all just backward
induction, which is what I'm

00:35:08.068 --> 00:35:08.768
teaching you.
 

00:35:08.768 --> 00:35:12.099
So the way computers play
chess, incidentally,

00:35:12.099 --> 00:35:17.739
is--and the guy who invented
this is Shannon,

00:35:17.739 --> 00:35:26.309
so he's a famous professor of
information systems,

00:35:26.309 --> 00:35:27.610
so an engineering professor.
 

00:35:27.610 --> 00:35:30.318
So he said, well,
you can't look at the whole

00:35:30.318 --> 00:35:34.074
tree which is too long in chess,
so what you should do--so all

00:35:34.074 --> 00:35:35.860
this extends way further.
 

00:35:35.860 --> 00:35:37.860
Maybe you can only look two
moves deep.

00:35:37.860 --> 00:35:41.733
So what Shannon recommended is
look as far as you can put in

00:35:41.733 --> 00:35:45.199
your computer,
apply some positional thinking

00:35:45.199 --> 00:35:49.820
to evaluate these positions at
the pseudo end of the tree.

00:35:49.820 --> 00:35:51.550
So it's really not a win for
white.

00:35:51.550 --> 00:35:54.476
Let's just pretend White's so
far ahead that we'll call it a

00:35:54.476 --> 00:35:56.559
win, and a loss,
and a draw, and a draw.

00:35:56.559 --> 00:35:58.679
That's just by looking at
positional values.

00:35:58.679 --> 00:36:01.630
And then having assigned those
terminal nodes values,

00:36:01.630 --> 00:36:04.903
now by backward induction you
can figure out what the value is

00:36:04.903 --> 00:36:07.909
here and exactly what the right
first move to make is.

00:36:07.909 --> 00:36:10.360
And after white's move black
will come here,

00:36:10.360 --> 00:36:13.666
black can now look two moves
deep, so black's going to look

00:36:13.666 --> 00:36:15.719
from here all the way down here.
 

00:36:15.719 --> 00:36:18.753
He's going to do his positional
evaluator to these nodes and try

00:36:18.753 --> 00:36:21.304
and figure out what they're
worth and then do backward

00:36:21.304 --> 00:36:23.760
induction to figure out what his
right move is.

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:26.628
Anyway, that's basically the
idea of all chess algorithms,

00:36:26.628 --> 00:36:29.447
and then they've gotten refined
by saying--wait a minute,

00:36:29.447 --> 00:36:31.159
there are lots of refinements.
 

00:36:31.159 --> 00:36:32.440
So I used to very interested in
this.

00:36:32.440 --> 00:36:34.610
I don't think I'll talk more
about it unless anyone wants to

00:36:34.610 --> 00:36:35.309
ask me something.
 

00:36:35.309 --> 00:36:37.869
So there's the origin of
backward induction,

00:36:37.869 --> 00:36:41.827
Zermelo's proof and it's
obviously a big deal in chess

00:36:41.827 --> 00:36:46.159
and the chess players all knew
about it before Zermelo,

00:36:46.159 --> 00:36:48.610
but they didn't write anything
down as formal as Zermelo.

00:36:48.610 --> 00:36:52.889
So how does this apply to
everything we do in economics?

00:36:52.889 --> 00:36:57.135
Well, I want to give a series
of examples culminating in

00:36:57.135 --> 00:37:00.608
market examples,
but starting off a little far

00:37:00.608 --> 00:37:01.690
from life.
 

00:37:01.690 --> 00:37:08.420
So the first one I want to give
is the red and the black.

00:37:08.420 --> 00:37:09.610
So these are just two games.
 

00:37:09.610 --> 00:37:12.594
This is the first one I
invented ten years ago,

00:37:12.594 --> 00:37:14.733
but I don't think
they're--anyway,

00:37:14.733 --> 00:37:17.199
I think they aren't that
original.

00:37:17.199 --> 00:37:18.550
I thought they were when I
invented them.

00:37:18.550 --> 00:37:21.409
But anyway, so the red and the
black works like this.

00:37:21.409 --> 00:37:27.476
There's a deck of cards,
52 cards, a deck of 52 cards,

00:37:27.476 --> 00:37:32.971
so half of them are--26 red,
right, and 26 black,

00:37:32.971 --> 00:37:37.550
which is all I care about the
cards.

00:37:37.550 --> 00:37:39.619
And someone offers you a game
and they say,

00:37:39.619 --> 00:37:43.550
okay, the deck is upside down,
they've been shuffled,

00:37:43.550 --> 00:37:47.262
you can turn over a card and if
it's black I'll pay you 1

00:37:47.262 --> 00:37:47.860
dollar.
 

00:37:47.860 --> 00:37:50.329
If it's red you have to pay me
1 dollar.

00:37:50.329 --> 00:37:55.054
So I'm offering you this chance
to play this game and of course

00:37:55.054 --> 00:37:57.800
you can quit whenever you want
to.

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:01.608
I can't keep forcing you to
play, so anytime you want to you

00:38:01.608 --> 00:38:02.320
can quit.
 

00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:11.920
So that's the game,
can stop whenever you want.

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:14.329
And once you draw the card you
throw it away.

00:38:14.329 --> 00:38:18.655
And so all these examples are
going to be examples of stopping

00:38:18.655 --> 00:38:22.414
games and you'll see in
economics that when you prepay

00:38:22.414 --> 00:38:27.309
on a mortgage or when you call a
bond you're stopping the thing,

00:38:27.309 --> 00:38:29.050
the contract's ending.
 

00:38:29.050 --> 00:38:31.355
Life is going on,
but that contract is ending,

00:38:31.355 --> 00:38:33.659
so want to know,
when's the right time to take

00:38:33.659 --> 00:38:34.889
an action like that?
 

00:38:34.889 --> 00:38:38.221
So red and black is a simple
game like that where you turn

00:38:38.221 --> 00:38:39.039
over a card.
 

00:38:39.039 --> 00:38:41.719
If it's black,
you're in the black you win 1

00:38:41.719 --> 00:38:42.280
dollar.
 

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:46.356
If it's red you lose 1 dollar
and you can stop whenever you

00:38:46.356 --> 00:38:46.849
want.
 

00:38:46.849 --> 00:38:51.163
So you have an option,
so call this an option,

00:38:51.163 --> 00:38:55.858
and most people totally
underestimate the value of

00:38:55.858 --> 00:38:57.010
options.
 

00:38:57.010 --> 00:39:00.867
So let's just figure out how to
figure out the optimal thing to

00:39:00.867 --> 00:39:01.179
do.
 

00:39:01.179 --> 00:39:02.530
What would you do in this game?
 

00:39:02.530 --> 00:39:05.059
Would you play if I gave you
the chance to play?

00:39:05.059 --> 00:39:07.500
I think I did this on the very
first day.

00:39:07.500 --> 00:39:10.210
Yes, you're about to say
something?

00:39:10.210 --> 00:39:12.610
Your hand twitched.
 

00:39:12.610 --> 00:39:15.536
Student: I was going to
say we have deceasing marginal

00:39:15.536 --> 00:39:17.244
utility as well,
so assuming we have

00:39:17.244 --> 00:39:18.659
&gt;
 

00:39:18.659 --> 00:39:21.726
you wouldn't play the game
because you would derive less

00:39:21.726 --> 00:39:24.123
utility from winning 1 dollar
than you would

00:39:24.123 --> 00:39:25.739
&gt;
 

00:39:25.739 --> 00:39:30.599
in magnitude that the loss
&gt;

00:39:30.599 --> 00:39:33.414
Prof: So I'm going to
now disagree with what you said,

00:39:33.414 --> 00:39:35.340
but it's very interesting what
he said.

00:39:35.340 --> 00:39:37.570
He said, look,
if you draw a card at the

00:39:37.570 --> 00:39:40.889
beginning it's 50/50 whether
you're going to win or not.

00:39:40.889 --> 00:39:42.309
If you win you get 1 dollar.
 

00:39:42.309 --> 00:39:45.809
If you lose you lose 1 dollar,
50/50 chance.

00:39:45.809 --> 00:39:50.543
If you're a little bit afraid,
if a 1 dollar loss is more

00:39:50.543 --> 00:39:55.701
important to you than a 1 dollar
gain right away it's not very

00:39:55.701 --> 00:39:58.461
good odds,
I mean, it's barely even,

00:39:58.461 --> 00:40:02.164
and if you're a little bit risk
averse and it's barely even you

00:40:02.164 --> 00:40:03.239
shouldn't play.
 

00:40:03.239 --> 00:40:07.409
But now, is it really barely
even, this game?

00:40:07.409 --> 00:40:08.199
Yep.
 

00:40:08.199 --> 00:40:10.965
Student: Well,
I mean, I think you should play

00:40:10.965 --> 00:40:14.050
because even if you get the
first 26 red at that point just

00:40:14.050 --> 00:40:17.135
go to the end and you haven't
lost anything except the time

00:40:17.135 --> 00:40:19.050
you've spent playing the game.
 

00:40:19.050 --> 00:40:21.652
You might as well play on the
off chance that you'll get some

00:40:21.652 --> 00:40:22.518
blacks ones first.
 

00:40:22.518 --> 00:40:24.617
Prof: Right,
so you can't possibly lose if

00:40:24.617 --> 00:40:25.579
you play this right.
 

00:40:25.579 --> 00:40:27.380
You can always go to the very
end of the deck.

00:40:27.380 --> 00:40:29.619
We're ignoring a good point.
 

00:40:29.619 --> 00:40:32.496
We're ignoring your utility of
time, so you can always go to

00:40:32.496 --> 00:40:34.789
the end of the deck and assure
yourself of 0.

00:40:34.789 --> 00:40:39.563
So this is actually a pretty
valuable option to be able to

00:40:39.563 --> 00:40:41.239
stop like he says.
 

00:40:41.239 --> 00:40:43.978
If the first one's black you
could stop and then you've won 1

00:40:43.978 --> 00:40:44.389
dollar.
 

00:40:44.389 --> 00:40:46.369
If a whole bunch of them are
red and you lose,

00:40:46.369 --> 00:40:49.099
well, you can always go to the
end of the deck and get zero.

00:40:49.099 --> 00:40:50.824
So you're never going to lose
and you have a chance of

00:40:50.824 --> 00:40:51.150
winning.
 

00:40:51.150 --> 00:40:52.320
So obviously you should play.
 

00:40:52.320 --> 00:40:56.188
Even if you are risk averse you
should play, but now the

00:40:56.188 --> 00:40:58.579
question is can we tell exactly.
 

00:40:58.579 --> 00:41:00.179
Suppose you're risk neutral?
 

00:41:00.179 --> 00:41:10.039
How many dollars do you expect
to win would you guess?

00:41:10.039 --> 00:41:11.409
Yep?
 

00:41:11.409 --> 00:41:12.110
Student: 0.
 

00:41:12.110 --> 00:41:14.449
Prof: You'd expect to
get 0.

00:41:14.449 --> 00:41:17.811
Now he just made an argument
that you should expect more than

00:41:17.811 --> 00:41:20.780
0, because for instance he said
take this strategy.

00:41:20.780 --> 00:41:22.000
Pick a card.
 

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:24.869
If it's black you win 1 dollar,
quit.

00:41:24.869 --> 00:41:25.889
You're 1 dollar ahead.
 

00:41:25.889 --> 00:41:29.719
So at 50 percent of the time
you're plus 1 dollar.

00:41:29.719 --> 00:41:32.768
If it's red the first time just
close your eyes and play to the

00:41:32.768 --> 00:41:35.918
end of the game and you're going
to get 0 because you're going to

00:41:35.918 --> 00:41:37.639
win 26 times and lose 26 times.
 

00:41:37.639 --> 00:41:40.739
So that's equal to .5.
 

00:41:40.739 --> 00:41:44.340
So there's one strategy that
gets you 50 cents on average.

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:47.250
You can't lose and half the
time you'll get 1 dollar,

00:41:47.250 --> 00:41:49.489
but that may not be the best
strategy.

00:41:49.489 --> 00:41:54.967
Student: You can play a
bunch of times and at worst

00:41:54.967 --> 00:42:00.639
you'll break even and at best
you could get all 26 black.

00:42:00.639 --> 00:42:01.530
Prof: Right.
 

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:04.320
So he's saying this isn't
ambitious enough.

00:42:04.320 --> 00:42:06.445
This surely gets a half a
dollar, but you could do much

00:42:06.445 --> 00:42:06.800
better.
 

00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:08.059
Like, let's just wait.
 

00:42:08.059 --> 00:42:11.489
The first time suppose you get
1 dollar.

00:42:11.489 --> 00:42:14.858
Suppose you get black the first
time, so that gives you 1

00:42:14.858 --> 00:42:15.400
dollar.
 

00:42:15.400 --> 00:42:19.869
Now, the trouble is the deck is
starting to turn against you.

00:42:19.869 --> 00:42:23.489
Now it's 25 blacks and 26 reds.
 

00:42:23.489 --> 00:42:26.400
So what would you do then?
 

